      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Instructional / fitness clip — around 8–10 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting: Clean indoor/home gym or yoga-mat space; neutral background with soft key-light + ambient fill so torso, leg, and arm motion are clearly visible.\n* Sound: Ambient (mat contact, breathing); no voice-over (optional subtle inhale/exhale cues).\nScene Setup\n* Location: Flat floor with exercise mat; enough space for full leg and torso movement.\n* Camera: Medium-wide angle (slightly above waist-height or at mat level), capturing full body from head to feet — so you can see shoulder/torso rotation, leg extension, and pedal motion.\n* Subject: use reference image, Adult male, athletic or average build, wearing workout clothes (tank/tee + shorts/leggings), lying supine and ready to begin.\nAction / Beats (0–~9/10 s)\n* 0–1 s — Setup / Starting Position:\nLie on your back on a mat with knees bent and feet lifted off the floor (tabletop position). Place hands lightly behind your head (elbows wide), core engaged, lower back pressed gently into the floor.\n* 1–2 s — Lift & Brace:\nInitiate the crunch by lifting shoulders and head off the mat, using abdominal contraction — keep chin slightly tucked to protect neck.\n* 2–4 s — First Pedal Crunch (Concentric Phase):\nBring right knee toward chest while left leg extends straight (hovering a few inches above floor); simultaneously twist the torso to bring left elbow toward right knee like pedaling a bike.\n* 4–5 s — Switch / Mid-Motion:\nSmoothly transition: extend right leg and bring left knee toward chest as you rotate the torso to bring right elbow toward left knee — continuous bicycle-pedal motion.\n* 5–7 s — Maintain Rhythm / Core Rotation:\nContinue alternating sides in a controlled, rhythmic “bicycle” movement — core tight, legs extending and drawing in like pedaling.\n* 7–9/10 s — Controlled Finish:\nGradually slow cadence, lower shoulders back to floor with control, return feet to tabletop or toes on mat, and relax core gently — ready for next rep or finish.\nPrimary Muscles / Focus (What Bicycle Crunch Works)\nThe bicycle crunch engages multiple core muscles in a dynamic, compound pattern:\n* Rectus abdominis (front abs) — primary target; contracts to lift shoulders and stabilize torso.\n* Obliques (side abs) — strongly activated with torso rotation and alternating knee-to-elbow motion.\n* Hip flexors & transverse abdominis — help control leg movement and stabilize pelvis during pedaling motion.\nBenefits & Why Use Bicycle Crunch\n* Total core engagement: Simultaneously strengthens upper/lower abdominals and obliques.\n* Dynamic motion: Combines crunch with coordinated leg movement (like cycling) — improves coordination and core endurance.\n* No equipment: Easy to do anywhere with a mat — suitable for home workouts or circuits.\n* Versatile intensity: Can be done slow for control or faster for cardio/higher challenge.\nForm & Safety / Technique Tips\n* Don’t pull on your neck/head: Use your abs to lift; hands lightly support head without tugging.\n* Keep lower back pressed to floor: Avoid arching; anchors core and prevents strain.\n* Move with control: Quality over speed — coordinate breathing and movement rhythm.\n* Breathe: Exhale as you crunch toward knee, inhale during leg extension/switch.\n* Smooth rotation: Twist from torso, not just reaching with arm, to maximize oblique engagement.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
      "muscles": "(What Bicycle Crunch Works)\nThe bicycle crunch engages multiple core muscles in a dynamic, compound pattern:\n* Rectus abdominis (front abs) — primary target; contracts to lift shoulders and stabilize torso.\n* Obliques (side abs) — strongly activated with torso rotation and alternating knee-to-elbow motion.\n* Hip flexors & transverse abdominis — help control leg movement and stabilize pelvis during pedaling motion.",
      "benefits": "& Why Use Bicycle Crunch\n* Total core engagement: Simultaneously strengthens upper/lower abdominals and obliques.\n* Dynamic motion: Combines crunch with coordinated leg movement (like cycling) — improves coordination and core endurance.\n* No equipment: Easy to do anywhere with a mat — suitable for home workouts or circuits.\n* Versatile intensity: Can be done slow for control or faster for cardio/higher challenge.",
