      "gender": "male",
      "category": "abs",
      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional core-workout clip — ~8 seconds long\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral gym tones (cable machine, dark/grey floor, warm skin tones) with a primary key light and subtle fill to highlight the subject and cable path\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (cable pulley hum, subtle breath sounds), no voice-over (optional low-volume breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Standard gym cable machine with rope attachment, clean floor or mat, background slightly blurred so the subject and cables are in sharp focus\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low) to fully capture torso motion, cable attachment, and body alignment during the crunch\n* Subject: use reference image, Fit adult male, athletic build, wearing fitted gym attire (tank or tee + shorts/training pants), kneeling on pad in front of a high-pulley cable machine, rope attachment overhead\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Starting position — subject kneels facing the cable machine, holds rope attachment with both hands near temples/head, shoulders relaxed, hips slightly back, core braced. Focus on form and alignment.\n* 1 s–2 s: Prep inhale — engage core and bracing muscles, ensure hips locked in place (don’t hinge at hips).\n* 2 s–4 s: Crunch down — exhale while curling torso down and forward by flexing the spine, bringing ribcage toward pelvis with constant cable tension; elbows move downward, torso contracts.\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak contraction — elbows near thighs / knees, core fully engaged, hold ~0.3–0.5 s to capture maximum abdominal tension.\n* 5 s–7 s: Controlled return — inhale, slowly return to upright start position under tension (don’t let cable snap you up), maintain core tightness throughout.\n* 7 s–8 s: End pose — torso upright, core stable, rope directly above head, subtle chest up, small pause (~0.3 s) before fade out or repeat.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Rectus abdominis (front of core — the “six-pack” muscles) — responsible for spinal flexion as you crunch down against the cable resistance.\n* Secondary: Obliques (side core stabilizers), transverse abdominis (deep core stabilizer).\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Constant resistance throughout the range of motion adds intensity to the crunch and improves abdominal muscle strength more than bodyweight crunches alone.Useful for both aesthetic abs development and functional core strength that supports compound movements like squats and deadlifts.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Maintain a neutral hip position — avoid letting hips hinge or drop, as that shifts tension away from abs and onto hip flexors.\n* Keep hands/arms fixed near your head — your arms act only as hooks; the movement should come from spinal flexion.\n* Use a controlled tempo — slow descent and ascent keep tension on core muscles rather than relying on momentum.\n* Adjust cable weight so you can perform clean reps without losing form; too heavy loads often cause compensatory hip movement.",
