      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional core-workout clip — ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), Frame rate: 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Neutral gym or home studio tones — dark mat or floor, warm skin tones, soft key light + gentle ambient fill to accent the subject and movement\n* Sound: Soft gym ambient (mat contact, breath), no voice-over (optional subtle breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean workout space (home or gym floor) with a mat; minimal clutter so viewer focus is on the subject and movement\n* Camera: Medium-wide ¾-angle (slightly low/eye level) to capture full torso and leg position, arms, and twisting motion clearly\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank or tee + shorts/leggings), seated with knees bent and core engaged\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject sits on floor with knees bent, feet either flat on mat or lightly elevated just above floor, torso leaning back slightly (~45° angle from floor), core braced, back straight. Hands clasped together in front of chest (or holding a light weight/medicine ball).\n* 1 s–2 s: Inhale to prepare — shoulders down and back, chest lifted, gaze forward toward hands/weight.\n* 2 s–4 s: Rotate right — exhale, twist torso toward the right side, shoulders leading the movement, hips stable, arms/weight moving in unison with upper body. Avoid rounding back; rotate from mid-torso.\n* 4 s–5 s: Hold twist — brief ~0.2–0.3 s pause at maximal rotation, core fully engaged, obliques contracted.\n* 5 s–7 s: Rotate left — inhale back through center (midline) then exhale as torso twists smoothly to left, maintaining controlled rhythm.\n* 7 s–8 s: End in center — body upright, core engaged, hands/weight still in front, short pause ~0.3 s with neutral spine, then fade/finish.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Obliques (side abdominals) — the principal muscles engaged during twisting motion.\n* Secondary: Rectus abdominis (front abs), transverse abdominis (deep core stabilizer), lower-back stabilizers, hip flexors (for support and balance).\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Rotational core strength: improves oblique strength and functional stability for everyday twisting movements (e.g., turning while lifting) and sports skills.\n* Balance & stability: training in V-sit position enhances neuromuscular control.\n* Versatile intensity: can be done body-weight or with added load (medicine ball, dumbbell, plate) for progressive challenge.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Keep spine neutral and chest open — avoid rounding shoulders forward.\n* Twist from the torso, not the arms — shoulders/upper back should lead the rotation, arms follow.\n* Movement should be controlled and smooth — avoid jerking or rapid bouncing.\n* Beginners may keep feet on the floor; more advanced can elevate feet slightly for greater core demand.",
      "character_prompt": "Subject: Adult male, athletic build, fitness attire. Relaxed standing A-pose, neutral expression.\nClothing: Athletic sportswear, workout gym clothes.\nStyle: Photo-realistic turnaround reference sheet, clean soft studio lighting.\nBackground: Clean, solid neutral gray studio background.",
