      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / instructional core-workout clip — ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Natural or soft gym lighting (neutral floor/mat, subject in warm tones), soft key light + ambient fill to isolate movement\n* Sound: Subtle gym or studio ambient (mat contact, breath), no voice-over (optional soft breath cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Workout mat on floor (home or gym); uncluttered background so focus is on movement and lower abs\n* Camera: Medium-wide shot (¾-angle or slightly side) capturing full torso and legs — torso from shoulders to hips and knees clearly visible\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male, wearing fitted workout clothes (tank or tee + shorts/leggings), lying supine on mat and ready to perform reverse crunch\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Setup — subject lies face-up on mat, arms by sides or lightly supporting hips for balance, knees bent at ~90°, feet lifted so thighs are vertical and shins parallel to floor. Core engaged.\n* 1 s–2 s: Brace — inhale deeply, draw belly button toward spine, stabilizing the core before initiating movement.\n* 2 s–4 s: Upward movement — exhale, curl pelvis and hips upward by contracting lower abs; knees move toward chest and lower back lifts slightly off the mat. Emphasize abdominal contraction, not momentum.\n* 4 s–5 s: Peak contraction — hold at top for ~0.2-0.5 s with core tight and hips elevated, highlighting deep ab engagement.\n* 5 s–7 s: Controlled descent — inhale, slowly lower hips and legs back to start position, legs still elevated and core engaged throughout. Avoid letting feet touch floor to maintain tension.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish pose — legs back at start, core stable, slight pause (~0.3 s) to underscore posture and muscle engagement before fade out or repeat.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Rectus abdominis — especially lower section, responsible for spinal flexion.\n* Secondary: Transverse abdominis and obliques — stabilizing core muscles that support controlled movement.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Targets lower abs: Great isolation movement for lower rectus abdominis without excessive spinal flexion.\n* Gentler on back/neck: Reverse crunch keeps head and upper back on mat, reducing strain often seen in traditional crunches.\n* Easy setup: No equipment needed — just a mat and controlled technique.\nForm & Safety Tips\n* Controlled tempo: Slow, fluid motion both up and down keeps tension on abs and reduces risk of lower-back strain.\n* Avoid momentum: Do not use swinging legs or thrust hips — the movement should originate from abdominal contraction.\n* Maintain neutral neck: Keep head and shoulders relaxed on the mat; avoid pulling on head/neck with hands.",
