      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic + instructional core workout clip — ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Soft indoor or gym lighting with neutral tones on a mat or clean floor\n* Sound: Ambient room/gym sound (soft breath, mat contact), no voice-over (optional subtle coaching cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor space with a mat in a gym, studio, or home environment\n* Camera: Medium-wide side/3-quarter angle that shows full body from shoulders to feet for clear visibility of the leg path and core engagement\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male lying supine (on back) with legs raised toward the ceiling, arms beside the body\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Start — subject lies on back on a mat, legs extended straight up (~90° relative to floor), arms alongside torso or slightly under lower back for support, core braced.\n* 1 s–2 s: Initiate Leg Drop — subject begins lowering both legs slowly toward the floor while keeping core tight, lower back pressed gently into the mat to maintain stability.\n* 2 s–4 s: Continued Lowering — legs continue lowering with control, stopping just above the floor (do not let heels touch), hips and lower back stable, core muscle engaged.\n* 4 s–5 s: Bottom Pause — legs held just above floor (~0.2–0.5 s), core braced, focus on tension in lower ab region.\n* 5 s–7 s: Raise Back Up — subject raises legs back up toward starting position at controlled tempo, exhaling, abdominals working to lift.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish — legs nearly vertical with core stable, brief hold (~0.5 s) then fade to black or reset for next rep.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Lower abdominals (rectus abdominis & transverse abdominis) — as the core stabilizes during lowering and raising.\n* Secondary: Hip flexors and supporting core stabilizers that help control the leg motion.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Strengthens the lower abdominal muscles and improves core stability.\n* Enhances controlled eccentric and concentric core engagement which supports posture and functional movement.\nAdditional Direction & Tips\n* Keep Lower Back Neutral: Ensure your lower back stays lightly pressed to the floor during the movement to protect the spine and increase core activation.\n* Controlled Motion: Avoid fast drops — smooth, deliberate lowering and lifting improves muscle engagement and reduces risk of strain.\n* Modifications: Beginners can lower legs to a higher angle (less toward floor) or perform single-leg drops (one leg lowers while the other stays raised), then switch.\n* Breathing: Inhale as you prepare, exhale while lowering legs; inhale as you raise legs back up.",
