      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic + instructional body-weight clip — approximately 8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting & Color: Soft, evenly diffused natural or gym/studio lighting; neutral tones (mat or floor)\n* Sound: Ambient room sound (breath, light floor contact), no voice-over (optional gentle cues)\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean floor space with a yoga or exercise mat — suitable for home, gym, or studio\n* Camera: Medium-wide angle (slightly low and to the side), capturing full body from shoulders to knees so the plank position is clear\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male in fitted workout clothing, ready in a modified plank position (knees on floor)\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Begin face-down on the mat; hands flat on the floor shoulder-width apart, knees on floor arthritic stable.\n* 1 s–2 s: Walk hands forward slightly so body forms a straight line from head to knees — shoulders above wrists, core engaged, hips level.\n* 2 s–4 s: Brace core and glutes firmly — maintain neutral neck, head, and spine alignment, avoid sagging hips.\n* 4 s–5 s: Hold stable — tension visible in core and midsection, breath steady, shoulders stable over wrists.\n* 5 s–7 s: Continue holding with proper form — maintain braced core, slight activation in obliques and lower back to stabilize position.\n* 7 s–8 s: Finish in plank-on-knees hold with clean bodyline; brief hold (~0.5 s) to emphasize stability before fade out.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Core muscles — rectus abdominis, transverse abdominis, and obliques.\n* Secondary / Stabilizers: Lower back (erector spinae), glutes, and shoulder stabilizers (deltoids & surrounding muscles).\nBenefits / Purpose\n* Engages core and stabilizing muscles with reduced load on lower back and knees compared to a full plank.\n* Excellent beginner variation for those new to core strengthening, returning from injury, or improving form before progressing to full plank.\n* Builds endurance and stability useful for everyday movements and improves posture by strengthening anterior trunk muscles.\nAdditional Direction & Tips\n* Alignment: Keep body in a straight line from head to knees — avoid sagging hips or raised butt.\n* Breathing: Inhale before you set position, exhale as you brace core and hold.\n* Modifications: Place forearms on the mat (forearm knee plank) to reduce wrist strain, or elevate hands on a bench/step for easier progression.\n* Progression: As strength improves, transition to a plank on toes or add shoulder taps to increase challenge.",
