      "full_prompt": "Style & Format\n* Cinematic / high-intensity workout clip — ~8 seconds\n* Resolution: 1920×1080 (Full HD), 24 fps\n* Lighting: Even gym/studio lighting that highlights subject form and movement lines\n* Sound: Ambient gym sound (foot shifts, controlled breathing, ball impact), optional rhythmic beat underlay\nScene Setup\n* Location: Clean gym floor or outdoor workout space with ~2 m of clear area\n* Equipment: One medicine ball (e.g., 4–10 kg depending on athlete level)\n* Camera: Mid-wide shot at ~45° (3/4 angle) capturing full body from feet to overhead\n* Subject: use reference image, Athletic adult male in fitted workout clothing, feet shoulder-width apart, ready at start position\nAction / Beats (0 s–8 s)\n* 0 s–1 s: Starting stance — subject stands tall with feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly soft, medicine ball held with both hands in front of chest (arms bent).\n* 1 s–2 s: Ready lift — engage core and glutes, extend arms, raising the medicine ball overhead while slightly rising onto balls of feet (creating upward momentum).\n* 2 s–3 s: Peak overhead — arms fully extended overhead, torso tall, core braced, preparing for powerful downward drive.\n* 3 s–5 s: Slam — exhale, forcefully drive hips forward and slam the ball down to the ground in front of feet; knees bend slightly as the subject follows the ball downward, maintaining neutral spine and controlled core engagement.\n* 5 s–6 s: Impact & absorb — ball hits ground with audible impact; subject transitions into a soft knee bend as hips hinge to retrieve the ball.\n* 6 s–8 s: Reset — stand up, lift ball back to chest or overhead (depending on style), brief stabilization pause with deep breath, ready for next rep; end on final powerful stance holding ball at chest with core tight.\nMuscles / Focus\n* Primary: Core (abdominals, obliques) — stabilization and explosive engagement throughout the movement.\n* Secondary: Shoulders (deltoids), arms (triceps, forearms), back (lats, upper) and lower body (glutes, hamstrings, quads) — for power production, balance, and ground force absorption.\nBenefits & Purpose\n* Full-body strengthening through explosive, controlled motion — enhances power, coordination, and metabolic conditioning.\n* Boosts core stability and dynamic strength due to rapid overhead lift and forceful slam.\n* Increases heart rate and calorie expenditure, making it useful for strength-power training and conditioning circuits.\nAdditional Direction & Tips\n* Form priority: Keep core braced and back neutral during overhead lift and slam; avoid overarching the lower back.\n* Breathing: Inhale during overhead lift; exhale forcefully during slam.\n* Ball choice: Use a non-bouncing slam ball if possible to reduce rebound risk; start with a manageable weight to master form.\n* Progressions: After mastering standard slams, variations like rotational slams or side slams can further challenge core and coordination.",
